<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-06-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-06-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="375" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d375">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 339.41/5.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">British Chargé
                                    d’Affaires</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">British Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-06-17">
                                    <hi rend="italic">June 17, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I beg to thank you on Sir
                            Cecil Spring Rice’s behalf for your letter to him of June 2, in which
                            you are good enough to communicate the substance of instructions issued
                            to the U. S. S. <hi rend="italic">Castine</hi> for the protection of
                            foreign life and property in the Dominican Republic.* * *</p>
                        <p>Sir Edward Grey desires me to say that His Majesty’s Government trust
                            that instructions to protect British life and property in case of need
                            may be given to whatever vessel of war the United States Government may
                            decide to send to Samana Bay. You will greatly oblige me if with your
                            usual courtesy you could communicate in this sense with the Navy
                            Department.</p>
                        <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Colville Barclay</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>